### 2. The Definitive Root Cause
The Railway worker environment variable `DATABASE_URL` was set to:
```
postgresql://codesentinel_user:ZqrXa1IRhEvgxYSMJtgknltqAYV5svsf@dpg-d7j0ph7lk1mc73a74ep0-a.oregon-postgres.render.com/codesentinel
```

The code uses SQLAlchemy's `create_async_engine()` which requires the `asyncpg` driver. But `postgresql://` defaults to `psycopg2` (synchronous). This caused an immediate crash:

```
sqlalchemy.exc.InvalidRequestError: The asyncio extension requires an async driver to be used. The loaded 'psycopg2' is not async.
```

The crash happened at the very first line of the task (`from app.core.database import get_db_context`), because importing the module triggers `engine: AsyncEngine = _create_engine()` at module level.

The error handler (`_mark_failed()`) also imports `get_db_context`, causing the same crash recursively. Result: the scan could never be marked as failed, staying in "queued" status forever.

### 3. Fix Applied (Commit 2854bf1)
Added `_normalize_db_url()` in `database.py`:
```python
def _normalize_db_url(url: str) -> str:
    if url.startswith("postgresql+asyncpg://"):
        return url
    if url.startswith("postgresql+psycopg2://"):
        return url.replace("postgresql+psycopg2://", "postgresql+asyncpg://", 1)
    if url.startswith("postgresql://"):
        return url.replace("postgresql://", "postgresql+asyncpg://", 1)
    if url.startswith("postgres://"):
        return url.replace("postgres://", "postgresql+asyncpg://", 1)
    return url
```

